1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
And now, great stories from the past. But as usual, a few names for the blackboard before we begin.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:18,000
First, Beowulf. B-E-O-W-U-L-F.

3
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:31,000
B-E-O-W-U-L-F. B-E-O-W-U-L-F. B-E-O-W-U-L-F. Son of Enfield said.

4
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:39,000
Now, I wonder if any of you know what these old Anglo-Saxon storytellers were called.

5
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:52,000
They were called Glee Men. Glee means joy. And the Glee Men were bringers of joy because people enjoyed their stories and songs.

6
00:00:52,000 --> 00:01:04,000
Sometimes, when I sit by the fire and think about that story of Beowulf, I seem to hear the Glee Men playing his harp.

7
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:14,000
I seem to hear him say. So. So. What?

8
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:19,000
Bro, tell me we still know how to speak of kings.

9
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:26,000
The Speardanes in days gone by and the kings who ruled them had courage and greatness.

10
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:37,000
The Speardanes in days gone by and the kings who ruled them had courage and greatness.

11
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:44,000
There was Shield Sheafson, scourge of many tribes, a wrecker of meadbenches, rampaging among foes.

12
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:48,000
This terror of the Hull troops had come far.

13
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:56,000
A foundling to start with, he would flourish later on as his powers waxed and his worth was proved.

14
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:01,000
Yet he lived and prospered, grew in strength and stature under the heavens.

15
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:08,000
In the end, each clan on the outlying coasts beyond the Whale Road had to yield to him and begin to pay tribute.

16
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:10,000
That was one good king.

17
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:15,000
That was good kuning. He was a good king.

18
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:24,000
Afterwards, a boy child was born to Shield. Beowulf's name was known through the north.

19
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:30,000
And a young prince must be prudent like that, giving freely while his father lives,

20
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:38,000
so that afterwards in age, when fighting starts, steadfast companions will stand by him and hold the line.

21
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:44,000
Behavior that's admired is the path to power among people everywhere.

22
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:50,000
Shield was still thriving when his time came and he crossed over into the Lord's keeping.

23
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:56,000
His warrior band did what he bade them when he laid down the law among the Danes.

24
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:02,000
They shouldered him out to the sea's flood, the chief they revered, who had long ruled them.

25
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:10,000
A ring-whirled prow rode in the harbour, ice-clad, outbound, a craft for a prince.

26
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:13,000
And this beautiful ship, what a way to go.

27
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:18,000
And of course, it brings with it the notion that death is but a point of embarkation in a journey.

28
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:22,000
It must have meant so much to them, hence the effort of bringing this massive ship,

29
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:25,000
six tonnes at least, with light, all the way up here.

30
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:30,000
And of course, this is where Beowulf comes in, because the opening movement of the poem

31
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:34,000
culminates with a magnificent account of a royal ship funeral.

32
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:40,000
A boat with a ringed neck rode in the haven.

33
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:44,000
And there they laid out their lord and master, giver of wound gold,

34
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:47,000
in the waist of the ship, in majesty by the mast.

35
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:51,000
A mound of treasures from far countries was fetched aboard her.

36
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:55,000
And it is said that no boat was ever more bravely fitted out with the weapons of a warrior,

37
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:58,000
war recruitment, swords and body armour.

38
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:02,000
High overhead they hoisted and fixed a gold signal,

39
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:06,000
gave him to the flood, let the seas take him.

40
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:08,000
No man can tell.

41
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:15,000
No wise man in hall or weathered veteran knows for certain who salvaged that load.

42
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:20,000
Then it fell to Beow to keep the forts.

43
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:24,000
He was well regarded and ruled the Danes for a long time

44
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:27,000
after his father took leave of his life on earth.

45
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:31,000
And then his heir, the great half-Dane, held sway.

46
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:34,000
He was four times a father, this fighter prince.

47
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:37,000
One by one they entered the world.

48
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:41,000
Herogar, Hrothgar, the good Halga,

49
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:45,000
and a daughter, I have heard, who was Annala's queen.

50
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:49,000
A balm in bed for the battle-scarred Swede.

51
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:53,000
The fortunes of war favoured Hrothgar.

52
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:55,000
Mighty was he above all men,

53
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:59,000
and greater than all people were Hrothgar's people.

54
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:05,000
But Hrothgar grew old and could no longer lead his army to battle.

55
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:11,000
Therefore, said he, I will cause a mighty hall to be built

56
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:14,000
where my warriors may feast and rejoice.

57
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:19,000
By the shore it shall stand, by the sea and the marshland,

58
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:21,000
where all may behold it.

59
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:23,000
The Hall of Halls.

60
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:28,000
Herod was the name he had settled on it, whose utterance was law.

61
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:33,000
Nor did he renege, but doled out rings and torques at the table.

62
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:38,000
The hall towered, its gables wide and high,

63
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:41,000
and awaiting a barbarous burning.

64
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:45,000
That doom abided, but in time it would come.

65
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:51,000
The killer instinct unleashed among in-laws, the bloodlust rampant.

66
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:57,000
Then a powerful demon, prowler through the dark, nursed a hard grievance.

67
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:02,000
It harrowed him to hear the din of the loud banquet every day in the hall,

68
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:04,000
the heart being struck.

69
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:08,000
Grendel was the name of this grim demon.

70
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:15,000
Haunting the marches, marauding round the heath and the desolate fens.

71
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:36,000
So, after nightfall, Grendel set out for the lofty house

72
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:41,000
to see how the ringdanes were settling into it after their drink.

73
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:47,000
And there he came upon them, asleep from their feasting, insensible to pain.

74
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:53,000
Suddenly then, the God-cursed brute was creating havoc.

75
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:57,000
Greedy and grim, he grabbed thirty men from their resting places

76
00:06:57,000 --> 00:07:01,000
and rushed to his lair, flushed up and inflamed from the raid,

77
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:04,000
blundering back with the butchered corpses.

78
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:13,000
As the day broke with the dawn's light, Grendel's outrage was openly to be seen.

79
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:18,000
Night's table laughter turned to morning's lamentation.

80
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:21,000
Lord Hrothgar sat silent then.

81
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:27,000
The strong man mourned. Glorious king, he grieved for his thanes.

82
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:31,000
But the next night brought new horrors, did more murders,

83
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:35,000
manslaughter and outrage, and shrank not from it.

84
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:40,000
Malignant by nature, he never showed remorse.

85
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:47,000
Whoever escaped kept a weather-eye open and moved away.

86
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:57,000
So Grendel ruled in defiance of right, one against all,

87
00:07:57,000 --> 00:08:02,000
until the greatest house in the world stood empty, a deserted wallstead.

88
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:11,000
The Lord of the Shieldings suffered under his load of sorrow,

89
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:17,000
and so, before long, the news was known over the whole world.

90
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:27,000
Sad lays were sung about the beset king, the vicious raids and ravages of Grendel,

91
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:31,000
his long and unrelenting feud, nothing but war,

92
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:36,000
inflicting constant cruelties on the people, atrocious hurt.

93
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:41,000
He took over Heorot, haunted the Glittering Hall after dark.

94
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:47,000
No warrior dared to ride. No hero from that land came forth in courage.

95
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:53,000
To the Anglo-Saxon audience, Grendel's rampage was not just a random act of terror.

96
00:08:53,000 --> 00:08:57,000
In attacking the Mead Hall, he was attacking society as a whole,

97
00:08:57,000 --> 00:09:02,000
for here the rituals were enacted which bound their society together.

98
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:08,000
So the hall is the centre of not only social order, but moral order.

99
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:11,000
And when the monster comes in the night

100
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:15,000
and starts to tear the king's followers limb from limb,

101
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:19,000
it's time for the hero, Beowulf.

102
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:23,000
Greatest in might among men, noble and powerful was he.

103
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:26,000
Beowulf was his name.

104
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:33,000
BEOWULF

105
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:47,000
He heard tell of the raids of Grendel, how for twelve years the Danes had gone in fear of him.

106
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:53,000
He was minded to meet that monster, eager to conquer him in battle.

107
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:58,000
He ordered a boat that would ply the waves. He announced his plan.

108
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:05,000
To sail the Swan's Road and search out that king, the famous prince who needed defenders.

109
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:12,000
The warrior boarded the boat as captain, a canny pilot along coast and currents.

110
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:17,000
Men climbed eagerly up the gangplank, sand churned in surf.

111
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:22,000
Warriors loaded a cargo of weapons, shining war gear in the vessel's hold.

112
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:27,000
Then heaved out, away with a will, in their wood-wreathed ship.

113
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:31,000
I groeso oia, a gwynd.

114
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:40,000
A hwyliodh Beowulf dros ffordd yr alarch at i dyniad yn Denmark.

115
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:49,000
Over the waves, with the wind behind her and foam at her neck, she flew like a bird.

116
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:52,000
Until her curved prow had covered the distance.

117
00:10:52,000 --> 00:11:00,000
It was the end of their voyage and the geats vaulted over the side, out onto the sand and moored their ship.

118
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:04,000
There was a clash of mail and a thresh of gear.

119
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:09,000
They thanked God for that easy crossing on a calm sea.

120
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:16,000
When the watchman on the wall, the shielding's lookout, saw shields glittering on the gangplank

121
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:19,000
and battle equipment being unloaded.

122
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:22,000
The watchman feared greatly for the safety of his king.

123
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:28,000
Powerfully he brandished a huge lance and boldly he challenged them.

124
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:32,000
Ho there, what strangers are you?

125
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:36,000
How is it that you step on the shores of Hrothgar, the mighty king,

126
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:40,000
with shields in your hands and swords by your sides?

127
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:42,000
Do you come then to do battle?

128
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:45,000
The leader of the troop unlocked his word hoard.

129
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:50,000
We belong by birth to the Geat people and owe allegiance to Lord Hialach.

130
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:55,000
In his day, my father was a famous man, a noble warrior named Edgthio.

131
00:11:55,000 --> 00:12:04,000
He outlasted many a long winter and when on his way, all over the world, men wise in council continue to remember him.

132
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:10,000
We come in good faith to find your lord and nation's shield, the son of Halfdane.

133
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:12,000
Give us the right advice and direction.

134
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:16,000
We've arrived here on a great errand to the Lord of the Danes

135
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:21,000
and I believe therefore there should be nothing hidden or withheld between us.

136
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:25,000
So tell us if what we have heard is true about this threat, whatever it is,

137
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:32,000
this danger abroad in the dark nights, this corpse maker mongering death in the shielding's country.

138
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:36,000
I come to proffer my wholehearted help and counsel.

139
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:41,000
I can show the wise Hrothgar a way to defeat his enemy and find respite.

140
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:48,000
If any respite is to reach him ever, I can calm the turmoil and terror in his mind.

141
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:57,000
Otherwise, he must endure woes and live with grief for as long as his hall stands at the horizon on its high ground.

142
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:03,000
And so, greatly wondering, the faithful watchmen led the strangers to Heorot.

143
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:10,000
They marched in step, hurrying on till the timbered hall rose before them, radiant with gold.

144
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:14,000
Nobody on earth knew of another building like it.

145
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:19,000
Majesty lodged there, its light shone over many lands.

146
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:22,000
Then the watchmen sought the king, saying,

147
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:28,000
Almighty Lord, a band of warriors has just now come to these shores.

148
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:32,000
They say they would destroy the monster Grendel.

149
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:37,000
Their leader has a noble look such as only heroes have.

150
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:41,000
Hrothgar, protector of shieldings, replied,

151
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:45,000
Beowulf, I knew him as a child.

152
00:13:45,000 --> 00:13:48,000
His fame has reached me.

153
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:54,000
Seafarers say this fighting lord has thirty men in one hand's grasp.

154
00:13:55,000 --> 00:14:03,000
If Grendel is his aim, then great reward will there be for his courage.

155
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:08,000
The hero arose, surrounded closely by his powerful thanes.

156
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:11,000
Resolute in his helmet, Beowulf spoke,

157
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:14,000
Greetings to Hrothgar.

158
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:18,000
I am Heorlax Kinsman, one of his hall troop.

159
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:21,000
When I was younger, I had great triumphs.

160
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:25,000
Then news of Grendel, hard to ignore, reached me at home.

161
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:29,000
Sailors brought stories of the plight you suffer in this legendary hall,

162
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:36,000
how it lies deserted, empty and useless once the evening light hides itself under heaven's dome.

163
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:41,000
So every elder and experienced councilman among my people supported my resolve

164
00:14:41,000 --> 00:14:44,000
to come here to you, King Hrothgar,

165
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:48,000
because all knew of my awesome strength.

166
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:52,000
And so, my request, O King of Bright Danes,

167
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:56,000
dear Prince of the Shieldings, friend of the people and their ring of defence,

168
00:14:56,000 --> 00:14:59,000
my one request is that you won't refuse me,

169
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:02,000
who have come this far, the privilege of purifying Harrot,

170
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:06,000
with my own men to help me and nobody else.

171
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:11,000
Hand to hand is how it will be, a life and death fight with the fiend.

172
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:16,000
Whichever one death fells must deem it a just judgment by God.

173
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:20,000
Fate goes ever as fate must.

174
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:27,000
And Hrothgar smiled when he saw them, so strong they seemed and shining.

175
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:34,000
And when he looked upon Beowulf, his heart knew hope at last.

176
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:38,000
Hrothgar, the helmet of Shieldings, spoke.

177
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:43,000
Beowulf, my friend, now take your place at the table.

178
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:48,000
Relish the triumph of heroes to your heart's content.

179
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:51,000
Then a bench was cleared in that banquet hall,

180
00:15:51,000 --> 00:15:54,000
so the Geats could have room to be together.

181
00:15:54,000 --> 00:15:59,000
So the laughter started, the din got louder, and the crowd was happy.

182
00:15:59,000 --> 00:16:04,000
Weltheo came in, Hrothgar's queen, observing the courtesies.

183
00:16:04,000 --> 00:16:07,000
With measured words, she welcomed the Geat,

184
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:10,000
and thanked God for granting her wish

185
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:14,000
that a deliverer she could believe in would arrive to ease their afflictions.

186
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:17,000
Beowulf, the son of Edgthil, declared.

187
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:20,000
I had a fixed purpose when I put out to sea.

188
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:22,000
As I sat in the boat with my band of men,

189
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:25,000
I meant to perform to the uttermost what your people wanted,

190
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:29,000
or perish in the attempt, in the fiend's clutches.

191
00:16:29,000 --> 00:16:32,000
And I shall fulfill that purpose,

192
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:37,000
prove myself with a proud deed, or meet my death here in the meat hall.

193
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:42,000
This formal boast by Beowulf the Geat pleased the lady well,

194
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:49,000
and she went to sit by Hrothgar, real and arrayed with gold.

195
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:52,000
Then it was like old times in the echoing hall.

196
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:57,000
Proud talk, and the people happy, loud and excited.

197
00:16:58,000 --> 00:17:02,000
Till the son of Heafden desired at length to leave the feast,

198
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:04,000
be away to his night's rest.

199
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:08,000
Aware of the monster brooding his attack on the tall gabled hall,

200
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:11,000
from the time they had seen the sun's lightness

201
00:17:11,000 --> 00:17:14,000
to the time when darkness drowns everything,

202
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:20,000
and under its shadow cover, shapes do glide dark beneath the clouds.

203
00:17:20,000 --> 00:17:23,000
Hrothgar wished Beowulf health and good luck,

204
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:27,000
named him Hallwarden, and announced as followed.

205
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:30,000
Never since I took up targe and sword

206
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:34,000
have I handed over Heorot, as I here do to you.

207
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:38,000
Have and hold now the house of the dames.

208
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:43,000
Bend your mind and your body to this task, and wake against the foe.

209
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:49,000
There'll be no want of liberality if you come out alive from this ordeal of courage.

210
00:17:49,000 --> 00:17:52,000
The lord of the shieldings, their shelter in war,

211
00:17:52,000 --> 00:17:58,000
left the meat hall to lie with Welthil, his queen and his bedmate.

212
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:05,000
And before he bedded down, Beowulf, that prince of goodness, proudly asserted.

213
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:11,000
When it comes to fighting, I count myself as dangerous any day as Grendel,

214
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:16,000
so it won't be a cutting edge I'll wield to mow him down, easily as I might.

215
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:20,000
He has no idea of the arts of war, of shield or swordplay,

216
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:23,000
though he does possess a wild strength.

217
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:27,000
No weapons, therefore, for either this night.

218
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:31,000
Unarmed, he shall face me, if face me he dares.

219
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:35,000
Then down the brave man lay with his bolster under his head

220
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:39,000
and his whole company of sea rovers at rest beside him.

221
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:43,000
None of them expected he would ever see his homeland again

222
00:18:43,000 --> 00:18:48,000
