310
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:22,000
My plan was to pounce,

311
00:24:22,000 --> 00:24:23,000
pin him down in a tight grip

312
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:25,000
and grapple him to death,

313
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:27,000
have him panting for life,

314
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:29,000
powerless and clasped in my bare hands,

315
00:24:29,000 --> 00:24:31,000
his body in thrall.

316
00:24:31,000 --> 00:24:35,000
But I couldn't stop him from slipping my hold.

317
00:24:35,000 --> 00:24:36,000
The Lord allowed it.

318
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:38,000
My lock on him wasn't strong enough.

319
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:41,000
He struggled fiercely and broke and ran.

320
00:24:41,000 --> 00:24:43,000
Yet he bought his freedom at a high price

321
00:24:43,000 --> 00:24:46,000
for he left his hand and arm and shoulder

322
00:24:46,000 --> 00:24:47,000
to show he'd been here,

323
00:24:47,000 --> 00:24:50,000
a cold comfort for having come among us.

324
00:24:50,000 --> 00:24:52,000
And now he won't be long for this world.

325
00:24:52,000 --> 00:24:54,000
He's done his worst,

326
00:24:54,000 --> 00:24:56,000
but the wound will end him.

327
00:24:56,000 --> 00:24:59,000
He is hasped and hooped and harpling with pain,

328
00:24:59,000 --> 00:25:01,000
limping and looped in it,

329
00:25:01,000 --> 00:25:03,000
like a man outlawed for wickedness.

330
00:25:03,000 --> 00:25:07,000
He must await the mighty judgment of God in majesty.

331
00:25:08,000 --> 00:25:11,000
Then Halfdane's son presented Beowulf

332
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:14,000
with a gold standard as a victory gift,

333
00:25:14,000 --> 00:25:16,000
an embroidered banner,

334
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:19,000
also breast mail and a helmet.

335
00:25:19,000 --> 00:25:21,000
And a sword carried high

336
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:25,000
that was both precious object and token of honor.

337
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:27,000
Come now to a banquet.

338
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:29,000
We'll celebrate with song,

339
00:25:29,000 --> 00:25:32,000
old tales of victory.

340
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:36,000
So Beowulf drank his drink at ease.

341
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:40,000
It was hardly a shame to be showered with such gifts

342
00:25:40,000 --> 00:25:42,000
in front of the hall troops.

343
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:46,000
They sang then and played to please the hero,

344
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:49,000
words and music for their warrior prince,

345
00:25:49,000 --> 00:25:52,000
harp tunes and tales of adventure.

346
00:25:52,000 --> 00:25:55,000
There were high times on the hall benches,

347
00:25:55,000 --> 00:25:58,000
and the king's poet performed his part

348
00:25:58,000 --> 00:26:01,000
with the saga of Finn and his sons,

349
00:26:01,000 --> 00:26:05,000
unfolding the tale of that fierce attack in Friesland

350
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:09,000
when Gnaf, king of the Danes, met death

351
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:13,000
and his sister Hildibur suffered cruelly.

352
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:18,000
Son and brother, she lost them both on the battlefield.

353
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:22,000
They foredoomed, cut down and spear-gored.

354
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:27,000
She, in shock, waylaid by grief, Hock's daughter.

355
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:31,000
How could she not lament her fate when morning came

356
00:26:31,000 --> 00:26:34,000
and the light broke on her murdered dears?

357
00:26:34,000 --> 00:26:37,000
So a truce was offered as follows.

358
00:26:37,000 --> 00:26:40,000
First, separate quarters to be cleared for the Danes,

359
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:43,000
hall and throne to be shared with the Frisians.

360
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:48,000
With oaths to Hengist, Finn swore openly, solemnly,

361
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:52,000
that the battle survivors would be guaranteed honour and status.

362
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:57,000
No infringement by word or deed, no provocation would be permitted.

363
00:26:57,000 --> 00:27:00,000
Their own ring-giver was dead and gone.

364
00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:04,000
They were leaderless, in forced allegiance to his murderer.

365
00:27:04,000 --> 00:27:08,000
A funeral pyre was then prepared.

366
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:12,000
Effulgent gold brought out from the hoard.

367
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:17,000
The pride and prince of the shieldings lay awaiting the flame.

368
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:22,000
Then Hildibur ordered her own son's body to be burnt with Gnafs,

369
00:27:22,000 --> 00:27:27,000
the flesh on his bones to sputter and blaze beside his uncle's.

370
00:27:27,000 --> 00:27:30,000
The woman wailed and sang keens.

371
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:35,000
The warrior went up. Carcass flame swirled and fumed.

372
00:27:35,000 --> 00:27:40,000
They stood round the burial mound and howled as heads melted,

373
00:27:40,000 --> 00:27:44,000
crusted gashes spattered and ran bloody matter.

374
00:27:44,000 --> 00:27:49,000
Warriors scattered to homes and forts all over Friesland.

375
00:27:49,000 --> 00:27:55,000
Hengist stayed, lived out that whole resentful, blood-sullen winter with Finn,

376
00:27:55,000 --> 00:27:59,000
homesick and helpless.

377
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:04,000
Then winter was gone. Earth's lap grew lovely.

378
00:28:04,000 --> 00:28:08,000
Longing woke in the cooped-up exile for a voyage home,

379
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:12,000
but more for vengeance, some way of bringing things to a head.

380
00:28:12,000 --> 00:28:16,000
His sword-arm hankered to greet the dudes.

381
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:21,000
Thus blood was spilled, the gallant Finn slain in his home.

382
00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:24,000
The wildness in them had to brim over.

383
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:27,000
The hall ran red with blood of enemies.

384
00:28:27,000 --> 00:28:30,000
Finn was cut down, the queen brought away,

385
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:34,000
everything the shieldings could find inside Finn's walls.

386
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:40,000
The Frisian king's gold collars and gemstones swept off to the ship.

387
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:43,000
Over sea lanes then, back to Daneland,

388
00:28:43,000 --> 00:28:47,000
the warrior troop bore that lady home.

389
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:55,000
The poem was over. The poet had performed.

390
00:28:55,000 --> 00:28:58,000
A pleasant murmur started on the benches.

391
00:28:58,000 --> 00:29:03,000
The stewards did the rounds with wine and splendid jugs.

392
00:29:03,000 --> 00:29:05,000
The queen spoke to Hrothgar.

393
00:29:05,000 --> 00:29:10,000
Herod is cleansed. The ring hall bright again.

394
00:29:10,000 --> 00:29:17,000
So, give while you may, generous lord, great rewards.

395
00:29:19,000 --> 00:29:24,000
She turned then to the bench where her boys sat, all the youth together.

396
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:29,000
And that good man, Beowulf the Geat, sat between the brothers.

397
00:29:29,000 --> 00:29:33,000
The cup was carried to him, kind words spoken and welcomed,

398
00:29:33,000 --> 00:29:36,000
and a wealth of gold given to the hero.

399
00:29:36,000 --> 00:29:39,000
Two arm bangles, a male shirt and rings,

400
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:44,000
and the most resplendent torc of gold I ever heard tell of

401
00:29:44,000 --> 00:29:48,000
anywhere on earth or under heaven.

402
00:29:48,000 --> 00:29:52,000
Then the queen pronounced, in the presence of the company,

403
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:55,000
Cymher di a gem hareth hwn.

404
00:29:56,000 --> 00:29:58,000
Fanwyl, Beowulf.

405
