medieval mind, and maybe to us still too, even more threatening, because it was female.

64
00:35:08,200 --> 00:35:14,640
Everybody gazed as the hot gore kept wallowing up, and an urgent war-horn repeated its notes.

65
00:35:14,640 --> 00:35:19,880
The water was infested, there were writhing sea-dragons, and monsters slouching on slopes

66
00:35:19,959 --> 00:35:26,000
by the cliff, serpents and wild things, down they plunged, lashing in anger at the loud

67
00:35:26,000 --> 00:35:27,959
call of the battle bugle.

68
00:35:27,959 --> 00:35:34,440
Grendel's mother may be fearsome, but she still feels a mother's bond to her child.

69
00:35:34,440 --> 00:35:38,559
And to the poet, that's even a source of imaginative sympathy.

70
00:35:38,559 --> 00:35:45,760
It makes her more than just a scary monster, she's a perverse mirror to mankind.

71
00:35:45,760 --> 00:35:50,720
The geat put on the armor of a hero, unanxious for his life.

72
00:35:50,720 --> 00:35:56,320
The manufacturer of the male shirt, figured and vast, that must venture in the deep, made

73
00:35:56,320 --> 00:36:02,040
it such a bulwark to his bone-framed chest, that the savage attack of an incensed enemy

74
00:36:02,040 --> 00:36:05,079
could do no harm to the heart within it.

75
00:36:05,079 --> 00:36:10,040
His head was encircled by a silver helmet, that was to strike down through the swirl

76
00:36:10,040 --> 00:36:13,440
of water, disturb the depths.

77
00:36:13,440 --> 00:36:18,760
Adorned with treasure, clasped with royal bands, it was right as at first, when the

78
00:36:18,760 --> 00:36:24,119
weaponsmith had wonderfully made it, so that no sword should afterward be able to cut through

79
00:36:24,119 --> 00:36:28,000
the defending wild boars that faced about it.

80
00:36:28,000 --> 00:36:35,200
And another item, lent by Unferth, a rare and ancient sword, named Grunting.

81
00:36:35,200 --> 00:36:40,040
The iron blade, with its ill-boding patterns, had been tempered in blood.

82
00:36:40,040 --> 00:36:44,440
It had never failed the hand of anyone who hefted it in battle.

83
00:36:44,440 --> 00:36:50,000
The Anglo-Saxons believed in the reality of supernatural forces, that could only be defeated

84
00:36:50,000 --> 00:36:56,320
by magic, whether by the cross of the saintly exorcist, or by the sword of the hero.

85
00:36:56,320 --> 00:36:59,320
Beowulf, son of Edgthor, spoke.

86
00:36:59,320 --> 00:37:04,040
Wisest of kings, now that I have come to the point of action, I ask you to recall what

87
00:37:04,040 --> 00:37:09,480
we said earlier, that you, son of Halfdane and gold friend to retainers, that you, if

88
00:37:09,480 --> 00:37:14,519
I should fall and suffer death while serving your cause, would act like a father to me

89
00:37:14,519 --> 00:37:16,359
afterwards.

90
00:37:16,359 --> 00:37:22,720
If this combat kills me, take care of my young company, my comrades-in-arms, and be sure

91
00:37:22,720 --> 00:37:28,200
also, my beloved Horthgar, to send Helag the treasures I received.

92
00:37:28,200 --> 00:37:32,519
Let the Lord of the Geats gaze on that gold, let Hrethil's son take note of it and see

93
00:37:32,519 --> 00:37:39,079
that I found a ring-giver of rare magnificence, and enjoyed the good of his generosity.

94
00:37:39,079 --> 00:37:41,799
An unfairth is to have what I inherited.

95
00:37:41,799 --> 00:37:47,600
To that far-famed man I bequeath my own sharp-horned, wave-sheened wonder-blade.

96
00:37:47,600 --> 00:37:51,959
With hunting, I shall gain glory, or die.

97
00:37:51,959 --> 00:37:56,839
Without further ado, he dived into the heaving depths of the lake.

98
00:37:56,839 --> 00:38:05,239
It was the best part of a day, before he could see the solid bottom.

99
00:38:05,239 --> 00:38:15,480
Grim and greedy, the guardian of the waters that kept her hundred winters watch.

100
00:38:15,480 --> 00:38:21,959
The hero observed that swamp-thing from hell, the Tarnhag, in all her terrible strength,

101
00:38:21,959 --> 00:38:24,839
then heaved his war-sword and swung his arm.

102
00:38:24,839 --> 00:38:29,079
The decorated blade came down, ringing and singing on her head.

103
00:38:29,079 --> 00:38:34,039
But he soon found the shining blade refused to bite.

104
00:38:34,039 --> 00:38:38,020
The fabulous powers of that heirloom failed.

105
00:38:38,020 --> 00:38:41,119
He would have to rely on the might of his arm.

106
00:38:41,119 --> 00:38:46,760
A man must act so when he means in a fight to frame himself a long-lasting glory.

107
00:38:46,760 --> 00:38:48,919
It is not life he thinks of.

108
00:38:48,919 --> 00:38:52,840
The Geat prince went for Grendel's mother, seized her by the shoulder.

109
00:38:52,840 --> 00:38:56,159
He was not sorry to be fighting his mortal foe.

110
00:38:56,159 --> 00:39:01,280
And with mounting anger, the man, hard in battle, hurled her to the ground.

111
00:39:01,280 --> 00:39:06,719
She promptly repaid this present of his, as her ruthless hands reached out for him.

112
00:39:06,719 --> 00:39:10,760
And the strongest of fighting men stumbled in his weariness.

113
00:39:10,760 --> 00:39:14,080
The firmest of foot-warriors fell to the earth.

114
00:39:14,080 --> 00:39:19,159
She was down on this guest of hers, and had drawn her knife broad, burnished of edge,

115
00:39:19,159 --> 00:39:23,520
for her boy was to be avenged, her only son.

116
00:39:23,520 --> 00:39:28,479
Overspreading his back, the shirt of mail shielded his life then, barred the entry to

117
00:39:28,479 --> 00:39:30,479
edge and point.

118
00:39:30,479 --> 00:39:36,239
Which Theow's son would have ended his venture deep underground there, the Geat fighter,

119
00:39:36,239 --> 00:39:41,520
had not the battle-shirt then brought him aid, his war-shirt of steel.

120
00:39:41,520 --> 00:39:46,919
The ruler of the heavens rightly settled it as soon as the Geat regained his feet.

121
00:39:46,919 --> 00:39:54,080
Then he saw, among the armor on the wall, a giant sword from former days.

122
00:39:54,080 --> 00:39:59,760
This wonder was so enormous that no other man would be equal to bearing it in battle-play.

123
00:39:59,760 --> 00:40:03,159
It was a giant's forge that had fashioned it so well.

124
00:40:03,159 --> 00:40:09,599
The Geat champion, shaking now with war-rage, caught it by the rich hilt, and careless of

125
00:40:09,599 --> 00:40:15,760
his life, brandished his circles and brought it down in fury, the catcher full and fairly

126
00:40:15,760 --> 00:40:18,520
biting into the neck.

127
00:40:18,520 --> 00:40:27,400
The blade sheared through the backbone, the sword was gory, he was glad at the deed.

128
00:40:30,440 --> 00:40:36,760
The seafarer's leader made for land, resolutely swimming, delighted with his prize.

129
00:40:36,760 --> 00:40:41,960
His thanes advanced in a troupe to meet him, thanking God and taking great delight in seeing

130
00:40:41,960 --> 00:40:45,440
their prince back safe and sound.

131
00:40:45,440 --> 00:40:51,039
With high hearts they headed away along footpaths and trails through the fields.

132
00:40:51,039 --> 00:40:56,640
It was a task for four to hoist Grendel's head on a spear and bear it under a strain

133
00:40:56,679 --> 00:40:59,719
to the bright hall.

134
00:40:59,719 --> 00:41:03,400
Beowulf, son of Edstil, spoke.

135
00:41:03,400 --> 00:41:10,599
So, son of Halfdane, Prince of the Shieldings, we are glad to bring this booty from the lake.

136
00:41:10,599 --> 00:41:14,440
It is a token of triumph and we tender it to you.

137
00:41:14,440 --> 00:41:17,960
I barely survived the battle underwater.

138
00:41:17,960 --> 00:41:21,719
It was hard-fought, a desperate affair that could have gone badly.

139
00:41:21,719 --> 00:41:26,159
If God had not helped me, the outcome would have been quick and fatal.

140
00:41:26,159 --> 00:41:31,960
I have wrested the hilt from the enemy's hand, avenged the evil done to the Danes.

141
00:41:31,960 --> 00:41:36,239
It is what was due, and this I pledge.

142
00:41:36,239 --> 00:41:42,479
O Prince of the Shieldings, you can sleep secure with your company of troops in here at all.

143
00:41:42,479 --> 00:41:49,119
Never need you fear for a single thane of your scept or nation, young warriors or old.

144
00:41:49,119 --> 00:41:53,799
That laying waste of life that you and your people endured of yore.

145
00:41:53,799 --> 00:41:57,359
Then the golden hilt was handed over to the Old Lord,

146
00:41:57,359 --> 00:42:01,320
a relic from long ago for the venerable ruler.

147
00:42:01,320 --> 00:42:06,960
Then Halfdane's son presented Beowulf with a gold standard as a victory gift,

148
00:42:06,960 --> 00:42:13,559
an embroidered banner, also breast mail, and a helmet and a sword carried high

149
00:42:13,559 --> 00:42:18,760
that was both precious object and token of honour.

150
00:42:18,760 --> 00:42:23,520
And soon all was restored, the same as before.

151
00:42:23,520 --> 00:42:28,679
Darkness came back, the hall was thronged, and a banquet set forth.

152
00:42:28,679 --> 00:42:32,679
Black night fell and covered them in darkness.

153
00:42:32,679 --> 00:42:35,760
Then the company rose for the old campaigner.

154
00:42:35,760 --> 00:42:39,039
The grey-haired prince was ready for bed.

155
00:42:39,039 --> 00:42:43,440
And a need for rest came over the brave shield-bearing geat.

156
00:42:43,440 --> 00:42:49,479
The hall towered, gold shingled and gabled, and the guests slept in it,

157
00:42:49,479 --> 00:42:54,479
until the black raven with raucous glee announced heaven's joy,

158
00:42:54,479 --> 00:42:57,880
and a hurry of brightness overran the shadows.

159
00:42:57,880 --> 00:43:01,559
Warriors rose quickly, impatient to be off.

160
00:43:01,559 --> 00:43:05,039
The undaunted hero addressed Hrothgar.

161
00:43:05,039 --> 00:43:11,000
Now we who cross the wide sea have to inform you that we feel a desire to return to Helac.

162
00:43:11,000 --> 00:43:14,599
Here we have been welcomed and thoroughly entertained. You have treated us well.

163
00:43:14,599 --> 00:43:18,840
If there is any favour on earth I can perform beyond deeds of arms I have done already,

164
00:43:18,840 --> 00:43:24,280
or anything that would merit your affections more, I shall act, my lord, with alacrity.

165
00:43:24,280 --> 00:43:28,599
If ever I hear from across the ocean that people on your borders are threatening battle,

166
00:43:28,599 --> 00:43:31,080
as attackers have done from time to time,

167
00:43:31,080 --> 00:43:35,400
I shall land with a thousand thanes at my back to help your cause.

168
00:43:35,400 --> 00:43:40,400
Helac may be young to rule a nation, but this much I know about the King of the Geats.

169
00:43:40,400 --> 00:43:45,200
He will come to my aid and want to support me by word and action in your hour of need,

170
00:43:45,200 --> 00:43:48,880
when honour dictates that I raise a hedge of spears around you.

171
00:44:03,880 --> 00:44:10,159
The one who upholds justice and truth in the land, ruling as long as many can remember,

172
00:44:10,159 --> 00:44:12,960
may indeed say this.

173
00:44:12,960 --> 00:44:20,080
He was born to be the best of men, most dear Beowulf.

174
00:44:20,080 --> 00:44:26,200
And so the good and grey-haired Dane, that high-born king, kissed Beowulf and embraced

175
00:44:26,200 --> 00:44:30,679
his neck, then broke down in sudden tears.

176
00:44:30,679 --> 00:44:38,039
The embrace ended, and Beowulf, glorious in his gold regalia, stepped the green earth.

177
00:44:38,119 --> 00:44:43,159
Straining at anchor and ready for boarding, his boat awaited him.

178
00:44:43,159 --> 00:44:49,280
Sail-ropes were tightened, timbers drummed, and stiff winds kept the wave-crosser skimming

179
00:44:49,280 --> 00:44:50,280
ahead.

180
00:44:50,280 --> 00:44:57,559
As she heaved forward, her foamy neck was fleet and buoyant, a lapped prow loping over

181
00:44:57,559 --> 00:44:58,559
currents.

182
00:44:59,080 --> 00:45:03,359
Hwylio d'llong gan dorri trwy'r dwr a gadail tyr Denmark.

183
00:45:03,359 --> 00:45:10,080
Swift sailed the boat, dividing the waves, left the land of Denmark, returned to Hugallach's

184
00:45:10,080 --> 00:45:13,080
kingdom.

185
00:45:13,080 --> 00:45:18,400
Beowulf's return was reported to Hugallach as soon as possible, news that the captain

186
00:45:18,400 --> 00:45:24,400
was now in the enclosure, his battle-brother back from the fray, alive and well, walking

187
00:45:24,400 --> 00:45:26,280
to the hall.

188
00:45:26,280 --> 00:45:30,919
A decision was quickly made on the king's orders, and the troops filed across the cleared

189
00:45:30,919 --> 00:45:32,200
floor.

190
00:45:32,200 --> 00:45:37,119
He hankered to know every tale the sea-geats had to tell.

191
00:45:37,119 --> 00:45:42,599
He had been poorly regarded for a long time, was taken by the geats for less than he was

192
00:45:42,599 --> 00:45:43,599
worth.

193
00:45:43,599 --> 00:45:50,559
They firmly believed that he lacked force, that the prince was a weakling, but presently

194
00:45:50,559 --> 00:45:54,039
every affront to his deserving was reversed.

195
00:45:54,799 --> 00:46:06,679
Þa nwylaf Beowulf, rydw i yn rhoi i ti ystad o saith mil o wyrtheg, yr orsedd hon a neuadh

196
00:46:06,679 --> 00:46:13,239
yr orain y tyr, yn haeddu clod cyfran daelwng o iar.

197
00:46:13,239 --> 00:46:21,359
I bestow on you an estate of seven thousand cattle, this princely throne, and a hall greatest

198
00:46:21,359 --> 00:46:27,559
in the land, gloriously decked, worthy of praise, the portion of an earl.

199
00:46:27,559 --> 00:46:39,559
A lot was to happen in later days, in the fury of battle.

200
00:46:39,559 --> 00:46:46,679
Hielac fell, and the shelter of Heardred's shield proved useless against the fierce aggression

201
00:46:46,679 --> 00:46:48,880
of the Shilfings.

202
00:46:48,880 --> 00:46:57,599
The wide kingdom reverted to Beowulf.

203
00:46:57,599 --> 00:47:17,800
He ruled it well for fifty winters, grew old and wise as warden of the land.

204
00:47:17,800 --> 00:47:24,560
Fifty winters of north wind, a smorgasbord of words for snow, shackled ice, stalactite,

205
00:47:24,560 --> 00:47:28,439
stalagmite, Beowulf ruled his wide realm.

206
00:47:28,439 --> 00:47:34,680
Beard wintered with wisdom, bonecage large with gravitas, our hero held his homeland

207
00:47:34,680 --> 00:47:43,160
till, one dark and starstruck night, where the earth surges up, up, grassing and greenscaping

208
00:47:43,160 --> 00:47:51,479
A steep stone-bouldered barrow, burial ground, a dragon stirred.

209
00:47:51,479 --> 00:47:58,319
Guardian of glistening, glamorous gold, as yellow as black gold, crude oil, extracted

210
00:47:58,319 --> 00:48:05,800
from earth and murky sea, is black, and jewels, winking wealth, as mirrored, multifaceted

211
00:48:05,800 --> 00:48:09,719
as dragon is extravagantly green.

212
00:48:09,719 --> 00:48:12,880
What use have the dead for precious gems?

213
00:48:12,880 --> 00:48:18,079
What use has a beast for a treasure chest, except the glamour, the glimmer, the glow

214
00:48:18,079 --> 00:48:22,079
that lights the gloom of the hollow cave?

215
00:48:22,079 --> 00:48:28,040
Dragon guarded the treasure trove of a long lost tribe, as dragons, masculine, feminine

216
00:48:28,040 --> 00:48:33,400
and neuter, protect their progeny from predators.

217
00:48:33,400 --> 00:48:38,760
When someone on the run stumbled across the den, and accidentally on purpose purloined

218
00:48:38,760 --> 00:48:47,160
a jewelled cup, since money manacles man's mindscape, then, sensing evil, fled in terror,

219
00:48:47,160 --> 00:48:53,640
the green minder of Mother Earth, fauna and flora, flared up.

220
00:48:53,640 --> 00:48:59,599
Do not disturb the habitat of the wordworm, the wild one, for when a dumb beast speaks,

221
00:48:59,599 --> 00:49:05,479
they speak the sparkiest sibilance, spit a split-tongued truth.

222
00:49:05,479 --> 00:49:08,560
Let sleeping dragons lie.

223
00:49:08,560 --> 00:49:13,920
Three hundred winters of white words, dragonhood ruled their ring hoard, till the thief disturbed

224
00:49:13,920 --> 00:49:19,239
the treasure trove, and made haste to inform his master, his lord, who ordered the den

225
00:49:19,239 --> 00:49:25,359
be looted, the gleam of greed in his eyes, and a pardon granted the absconder, who wreaked

226
00:49:25,359 --> 00:49:28,680
the worst with that first theft.

227
00:49:28,680 --> 00:49:36,160
When dragon stirred, life stood still.

228
00:49:36,160 --> 00:49:41,560
The serpent sensed homo sapiens, scanned the thief's physical footprint, evidence the

229
00:49:41,560 --> 00:49:43,359
enemy had entered.

230
00:49:43,359 --> 00:49:48,239
The horde guardian scoured the ground, inside and outside, over and under, desperate to

231
00:49:48,239 --> 00:49:50,319
discover the intruder.

232
00:49:50,319 --> 00:49:56,400
Flesh famished and bloodthirsty, encircled the cave to catch the coward, but nothing,

233
00:49:56,400 --> 00:49:57,640
no one.

234
00:49:57,640 --> 00:50:05,680
Black in the barrow, hollow and dark as a howl, sought the gold cup, discovered it,

235
00:50:05,680 --> 00:50:07,199
gone.

236
00:50:07,199 --> 00:50:13,959
The sun was slow to sink on the sea, and with each hour, the heat heightened, every second

237
00:50:13,959 --> 00:50:20,680
incendiary, until darkness fell, and the fire of rage boiled in the breast of the barrow

238
00:50:20,680 --> 00:50:21,680
beast.

239
00:50:21,680 --> 00:50:26,199
For the theft of a cup, revenge erupted.

240
00:50:26,239 --> 00:50:31,239
The dragon took off in a frenzy of flames, scarring their name on the panorama.

241
00:50:31,239 --> 00:50:37,079
Terror gripped the earthscape, grief engulfed the heart of the Gaiats.

242
00:50:37,079 --> 00:50:44,680
So begins the end of the son of Edsthael, the brave, unassailable Beowulf.

243
00:50:44,680 --> 00:50:52,160
The fire-spitter spewed a word-horde, inflammatory invocation, hated, heated, and hunted, burning

244
00:50:52,160 --> 00:50:55,959
the burnished buildings and punishing the populace.

245
00:50:56,719 --> 00:51:03,839
Here, there, dragon waged war, but before the east orb opened its eye, they retreated

246
00:51:03,839 --> 00:51:10,160
to the banked barrow, the dark den of death, lit by the glittering, glistening jewels they

247
00:51:10,160 --> 00:51:13,680
guarded like golden eggs.

248
00:51:13,680 --> 00:51:22,400
Then Beowulf heard the murmurs, no-smoke-without-fire rumours, his own home, high throne, haven,

249
00:51:22,439 --> 00:51:30,640
hearth of Hygge, safe space, say it though the truth thickens your throat, had blazed

250
00:51:30,640 --> 00:51:33,760
in waves of flames.

251
00:51:33,760 --> 00:51:39,760
Fire-dragon gone on the rampage on the ramparts, it hit home in his heartbeat.

252
00:51:39,760 --> 00:51:40,760
Was it weird?

253
00:51:40,760 --> 00:51:41,760
What must be?

254
00:51:41,760 --> 00:51:46,280
What had he done to earn the sentence of God, the great creator?

255
00:51:46,839 --> 00:51:55,239
Beowulf, not himself, shipwrecked by self-doubt, doom-ravaged, declared revenge.

256
00:51:55,239 --> 00:52:00,640
The leader of the geats ordered a war-shield, fashioned from iron, impervious to fire, as

257
00:52:00,640 --> 00:52:04,079
woods from the woods would smoulder, combust.

258
00:52:04,079 --> 00:52:10,359
Time and weird were winding thin for the proud protector of the populace, and the serpent,

259
00:52:10,359 --> 00:52:14,280
though he'd shielded his horde three hundred hibernations.

260
00:52:14,800 --> 00:52:19,880
Beowulf, the prince of rings, resisted charging the dragon with a large army.

261
00:52:19,880 --> 00:52:25,959
He was not afraid of the fire-flayer, our protagonist, who'd done in, finished men,

262
00:52:25,959 --> 00:52:31,359
Grendel and Grendel's mother, the human, the superhuman.

263
00:52:31,359 --> 00:52:38,680
He'd battled, attacked and ransacked, witnessed grief, loss of life every which way, yet remained

264
00:52:38,680 --> 00:52:40,599
brave.

265
00:52:40,599 --> 00:52:48,040
Today he would face his ultimate fate, weird in the form of the wordworm, his nemesis,

266
00:52:48,040 --> 00:52:50,560
the serpent.

267
00:52:50,560 --> 00:52:55,040
Beowulf took just twelve men on his final fight with the fire-spitter, including the

268
00:52:55,040 --> 00:53:00,000
culprit who'd plundered the cup, spurring the dragon's extravagant wrath.

269
00:53:00,000 --> 00:53:06,199
This thirteenth man, this unlucky thief, was afraid to revisit the dragon's den, but only

270
00:53:06,400 --> 00:53:12,199
he knew the secluded route to the underground den, the stone hall near the crashing, thrashing

271
00:53:12,199 --> 00:53:14,119
sortscape.

272
00:53:14,119 --> 00:53:19,439
Take a glimpse at the gleaming gems, the showy stones of the treasure trove, you'll need

273
00:53:19,439 --> 00:53:23,719
guts to try to retrieve them.

274
00:53:23,719 --> 00:53:30,000
Beowulf the king, ring-giver of the geats, seated on the cape with a heavy care, wished

275
00:53:30,000 --> 00:53:36,959
his hearth-men good health and heart, hid his low mood, impending doom drawing nearer

276
00:53:36,959 --> 00:53:40,040
and nearer to our hero.

277
00:53:40,040 --> 00:53:47,680
Soon his body and soul would fork, his lifespan end, his life-spirit take wing from his bone

278
00:53:47,680 --> 00:53:50,680
bondage.

279
00:53:50,680 --> 00:53:56,560
As images flitted from his former life, seven years old, fostered by Threthil in the royal

280
00:53:56,560 --> 00:54:04,040
court, in awe of his kinship, the glitter of gems, the fire of feasts, an arrow pierced

281
00:54:04,040 --> 00:54:12,439
in Harrowbield's chest, freak accident, brother killed brother, war between Swedes and geats,

282
00:54:12,439 --> 00:54:17,479
the shining sword and precious treasure honoured to him by Heorlach.

283
00:54:17,479 --> 00:54:21,359
Beowulf, son of Eddsthael, said,

284
00:54:21,359 --> 00:54:28,479
At the blade's edge, of this tested weapon, this named slayer, Naegling, this hard sword,

285
00:54:28,479 --> 00:54:31,599
I'll recover the treasure.

286
00:54:31,599 --> 00:54:40,439
When I was young, I fought tough and survived, now I am old, I'll prove bolder, conquer this

287
00:54:40,439 --> 00:54:48,400
dragon fiend, for the glory of god, if it dares to surface, face me in combat.

288
00:54:48,439 --> 00:54:57,880
A simple chainmail, shield and sword, no boyish boasts or wise words, I'll face my rival.

289
00:54:57,880 --> 00:55:05,079
This is no knuckle fight with Grendel or his vengeful Virago, this is a fight against fire.

290
00:55:05,079 --> 00:55:15,079
I will not shift a foot, I will trust that fate, weird divine will, must decide who'll win.

291
00:55:15,079 --> 00:55:21,959
Wait here on the barrow, safe in your war gear, to see which of us bears our wounds best,

292
00:55:21,959 --> 00:55:26,400
who gives in first, who holds out last.

293
00:55:26,400 --> 00:55:35,199
It's my rite of passage, my battle alone, either gleaming gold or grimacing death.

294
00:55:35,199 --> 00:55:41,359
From the dragon's den, a stream rippled with flickering flames from the dragon's breath.

295
00:55:41,359 --> 00:55:45,040
Who could confront that heat?

296
00:55:45,040 --> 00:55:52,199
Behold Beowulf, wizened warrior, greying with greatness, king of the geats, hero in armour

297
00:55:52,199 --> 00:55:57,680
and shimmering shield, revealing the gleaming edge of his sword, the ancient heirloom named

298
00:55:57,680 --> 00:55:59,040
Nageling.

299
00:55:59,040 --> 00:56:07,520
He let one word burst from his core, a battle cry that boomed in the barrow, ricocheted

300
00:56:07,520 --> 00:56:10,319
off the grey stone cave.

301
00:56:10,319 --> 00:56:19,439
And his nemesis, the antagonist, fire starter, flame spitter, eco-hero, echoed back an earth-shattering,

302
00:56:19,439 --> 00:56:23,719
earth-dragon roar of flame, smoke and steam.

303
00:56:23,719 --> 00:56:31,520
Snaked out of the cave, uncoiled, fifty foot long, scaled and scalding, gold guardian,

304
00:56:31,520 --> 00:56:34,239
glittering green.

305
00:56:34,280 --> 00:56:37,920
Behold the beauty of the beast.

306
00:56:37,920 --> 00:56:41,880
Horrified, they mirrored each other.

307
00:56:41,880 --> 00:56:45,920
Then the creature coiled and collided with Beowulf's shield.

308
00:56:45,920 --> 00:56:50,560
It held out, but not as long as he longed for it, and when he raised his hand to attack

309
00:56:50,560 --> 00:56:56,880
his fierce and fiery nemesis, the cutting edge of the legendary sword failed on the

310
00:56:56,880 --> 00:56:59,479
bony scales.

311
00:56:59,479 --> 00:57:03,400
Played the wrong tune for a warrior in the heat of battle.

312
00:57:03,400 --> 00:57:10,079
The barrow-beast incensed an incendiary spat-back of barrage of battle-bites, and the son of

313
00:57:10,079 --> 00:57:17,239
Ed Sao took umbrage, but sprang back, gave ground against his will, as we must all one

314
00:57:17,239 --> 00:57:21,880
day concede the final defeat.

315
00:57:21,880 --> 00:57:24,719
But the fight is not over yet.

316
00:57:24,719 --> 00:57:29,479
These two enemies, twinned by fate, clashed once more.

317
00:57:29,479 --> 00:57:34,959
The wordworm took a deep breath, spewed a firestorm, and Beowulf was trapped in a ring

318
00:57:34,959 --> 00:57:39,000
of fire, he who had once freed his people.

319
00:57:39,000 --> 00:57:44,959
His men, armoured, weaponed and trained, did not advance, brave and warlike, to save their

320
00:57:44,959 --> 00:57:45,959
lord.

321
00:57:45,959 --> 00:57:49,520
They fled to the forest, to save their own skin.

322
00:57:49,520 --> 00:57:54,359
Except for one, known as Wiglaf, son of Weirstann.

323
00:57:54,359 --> 00:58:00,079
He couldn't desert his worthy lord, remembering the rings and rewards brave Beowulf had bestowed

324
00:58:00,079 --> 00:58:01,959
upon him.

325
00:58:01,959 --> 00:58:08,839
His hand grasping his shield and sword, Wiglaf cursed his cowardly companions.

326
00:58:08,839 --> 00:58:12,959
Remember the promises we made in the beer hall to Beowulf, how we pledged allegiance

327
00:58:12,959 --> 00:58:14,800
for this bloodshed.

328
00:58:14,800 --> 00:58:19,719
And though he swore on his ancient sword to go it alone, I would rather allow the flames

329
00:58:19,719 --> 00:58:26,599
to burn my bulky body to ashes, alongside my lavish lord, than desert him now.

330
00:58:26,599 --> 00:58:32,040
With that, he hurried through the seething fumes to meet his leader, with these words.

331
00:58:32,040 --> 00:58:36,760
Lord, I will support you.

332
00:58:36,760 --> 00:58:41,920
Hearing those words, the wordworm exploded with expletives.

333
00:58:41,920 --> 00:58:47,119
The fire flame swelled in waves and charred Wiglaf's shield to a cinder.

334
00:58:47,119 --> 00:58:52,599
His metal armor would not save him, only his king's shield conserved him.

335
00:58:52,599 --> 00:58:59,920
But now, recalling his past advantage, his legendary epic strength, Beowulf wielded his

336
00:58:59,920 --> 00:59:08,479
battle blade with such power, it stuck in the skull of the winged one, niggling shattered.

337
00:59:08,479 --> 00:59:15,479
Such was Beowulf's brute force, too superhuman for sword or shield.

338
00:59:15,479 --> 00:59:22,280
Then, for the third and final time, the firestarter, feeling his life force threatened, lunged

339
00:59:22,280 --> 00:59:29,040
towards Beowulf, fierce and bloodthirsty, bit him in the neck with his bitter jaws.

340
00:59:29,040 --> 00:59:32,359
Beowulf bled, mortally wounded.

341
00:59:32,359 --> 00:59:35,520
His lifeblood flowed like lava.

342
00:59:35,520 --> 00:59:40,619
But Wiglaf remained brave and faithful, although his battling hand was burned.

343
00:59:40,660 --> 00:59:46,459
With his sword studded and bloodstained, he struck at the dragon, lower down, and the

344
00:59:46,459 --> 00:59:50,380
fire began to beat back.

345
00:59:50,380 --> 00:59:59,020
Then Beowulf, bloody, brave and bright-eyed, saw in that split second a lifeline.

346
00:59:59,020 --> 01:00:00,020
He drew the sharp knife.



1
01:00:00,000 --> 01:00:05,320
he wore in his armour and plunged it into the dragon's gut.

2
01:00:05,320 --> 01:00:16,559
The fatal thrust that snuffed out the flame spitter, and they fell, extinguished, earthed,

3
01:00:16,559 --> 01:00:18,980
extinct.

4
01:00:18,980 --> 01:00:26,040
These two men together, twinned warriors, had finally brought the dragon down.

5
01:00:26,040 --> 01:00:33,959
Big Love honoured the eleventh hour, but for Beowulf, it was his final win.

6
01:00:33,959 --> 01:00:42,759
His fate, his weird, his fatal wound, mirrored the doom of the wordworm.

7
01:00:42,759 --> 01:00:48,119
So Daring drove out life.

8
01:00:49,119 --> 01:00:59,000
Then the wound, dealt by the ground-burner earlier, began to scald and swell.

9
01:00:59,000 --> 01:01:04,959
Beowulf discovered deadly poison suppurating inside him, surges of nausea.

10
01:01:04,959 --> 01:01:09,680
And the king saw the last triumph of his works in the world.

11
01:01:09,680 --> 01:01:17,559
Wiglaf took water and washed his good lord, bathed away battle-blood, loosened his helmet.

12
01:01:17,559 --> 01:01:23,919
Beowulf spoke, in spite of his wounds, for he well knew his days in the world had been

13
01:01:23,919 --> 01:01:26,120
lived out to the end.

14
01:01:26,120 --> 01:01:34,800
His allotted time was drawing to a close.

15
01:01:34,800 --> 01:01:37,800
Death was very near.

16
01:01:48,559 --> 01:01:55,559
Now was the time when I would have wanted to bestow this armour on my own son.

17
01:01:55,559 --> 01:02:00,559
Had it been my fortune to have fathered an heir and live on in his flesh.

18
01:02:00,559 --> 01:02:04,559
For fifty years I ruled this nation.

19
01:02:04,559 --> 01:02:10,559
No king of any neighbouring clan would dare face me with troops.

20
01:02:10,559 --> 01:02:13,559
None had the power to intimidate me.

21
01:02:14,559 --> 01:02:17,559
I stood my ground and took what came.

22
01:02:17,559 --> 01:02:20,559
Cared for things in my keeping.

23
01:02:20,559 --> 01:02:22,559
Never fermented quarrels.

24
01:02:22,559 --> 01:02:25,559
Never swore to a lie.

25
01:02:25,559 --> 01:02:29,559
All this consoles me.

26
01:02:29,559 --> 01:02:32,559
Go now, quickly, dearest Wiglaf.

27
01:02:32,559 --> 01:02:36,559
Under the grey stone where the dragon is laid out, lost his treasure.

28
01:02:36,559 --> 01:02:39,559
Hurry to feast your eyes on the horde.

29
01:02:39,559 --> 01:02:41,559
Away you go.

30
01:02:41,559 --> 01:02:44,559
I want to examine the ancient gold.

31
01:02:44,559 --> 01:02:47,559
Gaze my fill on those garnered jewels.

32
01:02:47,559 --> 01:02:51,559
My going will be easier for having seen the treasure.

33
01:02:51,559 --> 01:02:57,559
A less troubled letting go of the life and lordship I have long maintained.

34
01:02:57,559 --> 01:03:03,559
Straight away, as I have heard, the son of Wayokstan obeyed his wounded lord, weak from the struggle.

35
01:03:03,559 --> 01:03:10,559
Following these words, he went in his ringcoat, his broidered battle tunic, under the barrow's roof.

36
01:03:10,559 --> 01:03:13,559
Traversing the ledge to the treasure house of jewels,

37
01:03:13,559 --> 01:03:19,559
the valiant young thane was thrilled by the sight of the gold gleaming on the ground where it lay.

38
01:03:19,559 --> 01:03:25,559
The devices along the wall and the den of the serpent, winger of the darkness.

39
01:03:25,559 --> 01:03:32,559
Drinking cups stood there, the unburnished vessels of a vanished race, their ornaments awry.

40
01:03:32,559 --> 01:03:38,559
Rusty helmets all eaten away, armbands everywhere artfully wrought.

41
01:03:38,559 --> 01:03:46,559
How easily treasure, buried in the ground, gold-hidden however skilfully, can escape from any man.

42
01:03:46,559 --> 01:03:50,559
Wiglaf went quickly, keen to get back.

43
01:03:50,559 --> 01:03:58,559
He was hoping he would find the leader of the geats alive where he had left him, helpless, earlier, on the open ground.

44
01:03:58,559 --> 01:04:07,559
So he came to the place, carrying the treasure, and found his lord bleeding profusely, his life at an end.

45
01:04:07,559 --> 01:04:12,559
The old lord gazed sadly at the gold.

46
01:04:12,559 --> 01:04:15,559
To the everlasting lord of all.

47
01:04:15,559 --> 01:04:21,559
To the king of glory I give thanks that I behold this treasure here in front of me.

48
01:04:21,559 --> 01:04:27,559
That I have been allowed to leave my people so well endowed on the day I die.

49
01:04:27,559 --> 01:04:36,559
Now that I have bartered my last breath to own this fortune, it is up to you to look after their needs.

50
01:04:36,559 --> 01:04:39,559
I can hold out no longer.

51
01:04:39,559 --> 01:04:46,559
Order my troop to construct a barrow on a headland on the coast after my pirates cooled.

52
01:04:46,559 --> 01:04:57,559
So that in coming times, crews under sail will call it Beowulf's Barrow, as they steer ships across the wide and shrouded waters.

53
01:04:58,559 --> 01:05:04,559
The Anglo-Saxons had a vivid sense of living in an old landscape,

54
01:05:04,559 --> 01:05:10,559
with prehistoric long barrows and standing stones all around them.

55
01:05:10,559 --> 01:05:16,559
The great stone circles to their poets were the work of giants,

56
01:05:16,559 --> 01:05:19,559
wondrous work of wall stones,

57
01:05:19,559 --> 01:05:22,559
wondrous work of wall stones.

58
01:05:22,559 --> 01:05:28,559
And the ancient stone age burial mounds were heathen burials,

59
01:05:28,559 --> 01:05:34,559
places where the ancestral treasures were stored up and guarded by dragons.

60
01:05:35,559 --> 01:05:43,559
Then the king, in his great heartedness, unclasped the collar of gold from his neck and gave it to his young thane,

61
01:05:43,559 --> 01:05:48,559
telling him to use it and the war shirt and the gilded helmet.

62
01:05:48,559 --> 01:05:51,559
You're the last of us.

63
01:05:51,559 --> 01:05:55,559
The only one left of the weighmundings.

64
01:05:55,559 --> 01:06:04,559
Fate swept us away, sent my whole brave highborn clan to their final doom.

65
01:06:04,559 --> 01:06:09,559
Now, I must follow.

66
01:06:09,559 --> 01:06:12,559
That was the warrior's last word.

67
01:06:12,559 --> 01:06:17,559
That was the warrior's last word.

68
01:06:18,559 --> 01:06:23,559
He had no more to confide.

69
01:06:24,559 --> 01:06:30,559
His soul fled from his breast to its destined place among the steadfast ones.

70
01:06:30,559 --> 01:06:41,559
The king had indeed met with a marvelous death.

71
01:06:41,559 --> 01:06:50,559
It was hard then on the young hero, having to watch the one he held so dear there on the ground going through his death agony.

72
01:06:50,559 --> 01:06:56,559
The dragon from under earth, his nightmarish destroyer, lay destroyed as well.

73
01:06:56,559 --> 01:07:04,559
Never again would he glitter and glide and show himself off in the midnight air, exulting in his riches.

74
01:07:04,559 --> 01:07:10,559
He fell to earth through the battle strength in Beowulf's arm.

75
01:07:10,559 --> 01:07:16,559
The treasure had been won, bought and paid for by Beowulf's death.

76
01:07:16,559 --> 01:07:21,559
Both had reached the end of the road through the life they had been lent.

77
01:07:21,559 --> 01:07:28,559
It was not long then till they budged from the wood, the battleshirkers, ten of them together,

78
01:07:28,559 --> 01:07:35,559
those traitors and weaklings who had not dared deploy their spears in their own lord's extreme need.

79
01:07:35,559 --> 01:07:41,559
They bore their shields ashamedly, their armor of war, to where the old man lay.

80
01:07:41,559 --> 01:07:44,559
They regarded Wiglaf.

81
01:07:44,559 --> 01:07:49,559
Wearily he sat, a good soldier, at the shoulder of his lord.

82
01:07:49,559 --> 01:07:52,559
Wiglaf spoke, Weachstan's offspring.

83
01:07:52,559 --> 01:08:00,559
Beowulf had little cause to brag about his armed guard, yet I found new strength welling up when I went to help him.

84
01:08:00,559 --> 01:08:06,559
Then my sword connected, and the deadly assaults of our foe grew weaker.

85
01:08:06,559 --> 01:08:09,559
The fire coursed less strongly from his head.

86
01:08:09,559 --> 01:08:14,559
But when the worst happened, too few rallied around the prince.

87
01:08:14,559 --> 01:08:19,559
So it is goodbye now to all you know and love on your home ground.

88
01:08:19,559 --> 01:08:23,559
The open-handedness, the giving of war swords.

89
01:08:23,559 --> 01:08:32,559
Our whole nation will be dispossessed once princes from beyond get tidings of how you turned and fled and disgraced yourselves.

90
01:08:32,559 --> 01:08:37,559
A warrior will die sooner than live a life of shame.

91
01:08:37,559 --> 01:08:43,559
He bade that the combat's result be proclaimed in the city over the brow of the headland.

92
01:08:43,559 --> 01:08:51,559
Now the people's pride and love, the lord of the geats, is laid on his deathbed, brought down by the dragon's attack.

93
01:08:52,559 --> 01:08:55,559
Now war is looming over our nation.

94
01:08:55,559 --> 01:09:01,559
Soon it will be known to Franks and Frisians, far and wide, that the king is gone.

95
01:09:01,559 --> 01:09:06,559
Nor do I expect peace or pact-keeping of any sort from the Swedes.

96
01:09:06,559 --> 01:09:10,559
This vicious feud, I am convinced, is bound to revive.

97
01:09:10,559 --> 01:09:15,559
They will cross our borders and attack in force when they find out that Beowulf is dead.

98
01:09:15,559 --> 01:09:20,559
His royal pyre will melt no small amount of gold.

99
01:09:20,559 --> 01:09:24,559
Heaped there in a horde, it was bought at heavy cost.

100
01:09:24,559 --> 01:09:33,559
And that pile of rings he paid for at the end with his own life will go up with the flame, be furled in fire.

101
01:09:33,559 --> 01:09:37,559
Treasure no follower will wear in his memory.

102
01:09:41,559 --> 01:09:43,559
The warband arose.

103
01:09:43,559 --> 01:09:49,559
They went unhappily under Arnanus to look on the wonder with welling tears.

104
01:09:49,559 --> 01:09:54,559
They found him on the sand, his soul fled, keeping his resting place.

105
01:09:54,559 --> 01:09:57,559
Rings he had given them in former times.

106
01:09:57,559 --> 01:10:05,559
But the final day had come for the champion, and the chief of the geats, the warrior king, had met his wondrous death.

107
01:10:05,559 --> 01:10:13,559
Stranger the creature they encountered first in the level place, the loathsome worm stretched out opposite.

108
01:10:13,559 --> 01:10:21,559
Scorched by its own flames lay the fire drake in its fatal markings, and it measured fifty feet as it lay.

109
01:10:21,559 --> 01:10:29,559
He had once been master of the midnight air, held sweet sway there, and swooped down again to seek his den.

110
01:10:29,559 --> 01:10:37,559
Standing by him there were bowls and flagons, there were platters lying there, and precious swords quite rusted through,

111
01:10:37,559 --> 01:10:41,559
as they had rested there a thousand winters in the womb of earth.

112
01:10:41,559 --> 01:10:44,559
Wiglaf spoke Werkstern's son.

113
01:10:44,559 --> 01:10:49,559
Often, when one man follows his own will, many are hurt.

114
01:10:49,559 --> 01:10:51,559
This happened to us.

115
01:10:51,559 --> 01:11:00,559
Nothing we advised could ever convince the lord we loved, our land's guardian, not to aggravate the keeper of the gold.

116
01:11:00,559 --> 01:11:07,559
Let him lie where he was long accustomed, lurk there under earth until the end of the world.

117
01:11:07,559 --> 01:11:10,559
He held to his high destiny.

118
01:11:10,559 --> 01:11:14,559
The horde is laid bare, but at a grave cost.

119
01:11:14,559 --> 01:11:17,559
It was too cruel a fate.

120
01:11:17,559 --> 01:11:28,559
Then Werkstern's son, stalwart to the end, had orders given to owners of dwellings to fetch wood from far and wide for the good man's pyre.

121
01:11:29,559 --> 01:11:36,559
They pitched the dragon over the cliff top, let tides flow and backwash take the treasure minder.

122
01:11:40,559 --> 01:11:42,559
It's a miracle it survived.

123
01:11:42,559 --> 01:11:51,559
Like all of Anglo-Saxon poetry, it's astonishing to think that the very root of our literary heritage only just got through.

124
01:11:51,559 --> 01:12:01,559
The faded ink, the singed vellum, the crumbling margins, carrying the word horde down to us.

125
01:12:03,559 --> 01:12:11,559
And the poem itself ends in flames, with Beowulf's body taken to a headland by the sea in his Geert kingdom.

126
01:12:12,559 --> 01:12:19,559
The Geert race then raised up a funeral pyre, shining mail and shields of war and helmets hung upon it.

127
01:12:19,559 --> 01:12:26,559
They laid out in the middle the body of their chief, and on top there then kindled the biggest funeral fire.

128
01:12:28,559 --> 01:12:35,559
The roaring of flames mingled with weeping, as the fire's red heart consumed the house of bone.

129
01:12:36,559 --> 01:12:40,559
Heaven swallowed the smoke.

130
01:12:41,559 --> 01:12:44,559
Beowulf is dead, gone down.

131
01:12:44,559 --> 01:12:46,559
Time tells his tale.

132
01:12:46,559 --> 01:12:49,559
Fever forth those favours, lord of fire.

133
01:12:49,559 --> 01:12:51,559
Rise, winter wind.

134
01:12:51,559 --> 01:12:53,559
Beowulf burns.

135
01:12:53,559 --> 01:12:55,559
Beowulf burns.

136
01:12:55,559 --> 01:12:59,559
The hero's boiled blood flows free from mountain peak to sea foam.

137
01:12:59,559 --> 01:13:01,559
He is free forever.

138
01:13:01,559 --> 01:13:03,559
His fame lives forever.

139
01:13:03,559 --> 01:13:05,559
The great worm killed our king.

140
01:13:05,559 --> 01:13:08,559
The black hill burns his bones to dust.

141
01:13:16,559 --> 01:13:22,559
Then the Geert people began to construct a mound on a headland, high and imposing,

142
01:13:22,559 --> 01:13:26,559
a marker that sailors could see from far away.

143
01:13:26,559 --> 01:13:31,559
It was their hero's memorial, as worthy of him as their workmanship could make it.

144
01:13:31,559 --> 01:13:40,559
And they buried torks in the burrow, and jewels, and a trove of such things as trespassing men had once dared to drag from the hoard.

145
01:13:40,559 --> 01:13:45,559
The beacon to that battle-reckless man they made in ten days.

146
01:13:45,559 --> 01:13:49,559
What remained from the fire they cast a wall around,

147
